My friend suggest as the 64-bit address space is so big you could just throw out random numbers and get a working &#x27;wrong&#x27; malloc.<p><pre><code>    void* malloc(size_t sz) {
        return rand() << 32 | rand();
    }
</code></pre>
Or in rustopia:<p><pre><code>    fn extern &quot;C&quot; malloc(len: uint) -> *mut u8 {
         unsafe {
             std::rand::random::<uint>() as *mut u8;
         }
    }
</code></pre>
Insert more so that it actually maps to memory.

What does malloc() return if it fails?<p><pre><code>    volatile char *x = 0;
</code></pre>
And what happens if you write to that address?<p><pre><code>    *x = 69;
</code></pre>
The answers to these questions, whilst not defined by the C language, are portable enough.
